				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The 2A03 is just a 6502 family CPU with different I/O and no decimal mode. As with any 6502 family CPU, you need ROM in at least the upper 256 bytes or so of address space ($FF00-$FFFF), in order to have somewhere to put the reset and interrupt vectors. If you want to actually do anything, you need RAM in at least the lower 512 bytes ($0000-$01FF).
<br />
<br />But you don't even need the upper address lines connected to anything. Notably, the Atari 2600 leaves A13 through A15 disconnected,[1] mapping the ROM into $1000, $3000, $5000, $7000, $9000, $B000, $D000, and $F000. It also puts I/O into $0000-$007F and maps the 128 byte RAM into both $0080-$00FF and $0180-$01FF.
<br />
<br />
<br /><span style="font-size: 75%; line-height: normal">[1] The 6502 variant used by the 2600 actually comes in a package that doesn't even have pins for A13-A15, /IRQ, /NMI, and a few other 6502 functions. Pins make up a significant fraction of the price of a chip.</span></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
