			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Code on the NES is usually $8000-$ffff because it's where its the most easier to map. It is necessary to have at least 6 bytes of ROM at $fffa-$ffff for the NMI, reset and IRQ vectors. (NMI and IRQ aren't required if you don't use those interrupts, any NES game will have to use NMI, but technically nobody forces you to use it, on a hardware project if you put NMI and IRQ pin high (with a coupling cap) you will have no problem).
<br />
<br />It is possible to map ROM anywhere on the NES, but you don't want it to conflict with anything else. Since $4000-$4014 are write only and (correct me if I'm wrong) returns open bus, it is possible to map ROM here (not RAM tough). $4015-$4017 are read/write, so you cannot map ROM here because this will conflict (altrough not all bits are used). It is possible to map ROM to $4018-$7ffff as well as $8000-$ffff with proper hardware (unless $4015-$4017 mirrors somewhere else, I don't remember in fact).
<br />
<br />The chip itself does not know what hardware is arround him, so if you power a 2A03 alone it will read from the reset vector, read open bus (most likely FFFF) and will jump to $ffff, read it, found $ff and since this is no valid instruction it will freeze or something. Prior to this the chip should try to write to $1ff and $1fe or something, phushing it's older adress and processor status as reset is also an interrupt. If you didn't connect /IRQ and /NMI to high, I'd be afraid things are much worse.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

